The total cumulative exposure–response curves (best linear unbiased predictions) showing the relative risk of infectious gastroenteritis according to temperature in the Japanese prefectures are summarized in Figure S5, along with the relevant lowest morbidity temperature and extreme temperature thresholds. The overall cumulative risk for infectious gastroenteritis showed generally a unimodal distribution at lower temperature and tended to increase at higher temperature. There was heterogeneity in the temperature–morbidity relationship across prefectures (Cochran Q test,
